
# Day 4 – Space Flight & AI

## Activities
- Learned about space flight and how artificial intelligence is used to support space exploration.
- Discussed how AI can help pilot spacecraft, plan flight paths, and perform complex maneuvers that allow missions to travel farther into space than humans can currently reach.
- Studied important physics concepts related to rocketry, including kinetic energy, velocity, gravitational potential energy, and rocket thrust.
- Applied these concepts while designing and building a prototype water rocket.
- Constructed the rocket using a plastic bottle, cork, water, foam board fins, a hand pump, and weights placed at the top of the rocket to improve its stability.

## What I Learned
Today, I learned that artificial intelligence plays a major role in modern space exploration by helping spacecraft navigate, make decisions, and complete missions with minimal human intervention.
I also learned how physics is essential to understanding rocket launches. 
We explored how kinetic energy, velocity, gravitational potential energy, and rocket thrust all work together to determine how high and how efficiently a rocket can travel. 
Building the water rocket helped me see how engineering, physics, and AI can work together to solve real-world challenges in aerospace.

## Favorite Part
My favorite part of the day was building and testing the prototype water rocket. It was exciting to take what I learned about physics and apply it to a hands-on engineering project. 
I also enjoyed learning how AI is helping scientists explore space and make future missions safer and more efficient. Seeing the connection between classroom concepts and real-world space technology made the experience both fun and inspiring.
